There are some very interesting takes on what could end up being the closest Senate race in the country. At the moment, the crowd here is estimating roughly 3-2 odds in favor of Warnock (D). Prediction markets are estimating pretty much the same odds in the opposite direction, favoring Walker (R). The forecasters are all at 50-50, and unlike some of the other close races, 538 is right there with them. It's interesting to see the diversion here, and I have to wonder if personal partisan bias is responsible for the way that different crowd sourcing communities are essentially in arbitrage on a race that isn't exactly wanting for information or analysis. I don't know what to do with this one, so I just averaged it all out. 52-48, Walker. I'd be surprised if that didn't change.

This is the race that I think 538 and PI are both biased the most in the R direction. Walker is leading in recent polls but can't break 50% in any, and is likely to do worse in a runoff than in the first round. In the event that the GOP has already secured the senate in November, and with Kemp no longer on the ballot, only the most engaged voters will show up for the runoff - i.e. the high educated and relatively liberal contingent who are unlikely to vote for Walker.

The last two polls have been fairly close, as partisanship becomes more of a factor with the election drawing near. Many Republican voters will turn out to vote for Governor Kemp. He's moderate and popular, and many Republicans have a strong dislike for his opponent. A few of these voters will not want to vote for Walker, due to Walker's scandals. Of those voters, a certain percentage will vote for Warnock, who is running as a moderate. But a certain percentage will vote for the Libertarian candidate. If this is enough to deny Warnock 50% of the vote, this will go into runoff. In a midterm election runoff that could very well determine control of the Senate, this should advantage Walker, if you look at past history.
